        of strong CO emission lines at 4.5 {\ensuremath{\mu}}m from an
        excess of dayside brightness in the Spitzer/IRAC/Channel 2
        passband. Using these models to constrain the reflected
        contribution in the CHEOPS passband, we derived an extremely low
        geometric albedo of A$_{g}$ $^{CHEOPS}$ = 0.027
        {\ensuremath{\pm}} 0.011. Conclusions. The orbital eccentricity
        remains a potential challenge for planetary dynamics that might
        require further study given the short-period massive planet and
        despite the young age of the system. The characterisation of the
        atmosphere of WASP-18 b reveals the necessity to account for
        magnetic friction and super-solar metallicity to explain the
        full picture of the dayside emission. We find the planetary
        dayside to be extremely unreflective; however, when juxtaposing
        TESS and CHEOPS data, we get hints of increased scattering
        efficiency in the visible, likely due to Rayleigh scattering.}",
